const faqs = [
  { q: "How does Whirlpool relate to Maytag, KitchenAid, Amana, and JennAir?", a: "Whirlpool Corporation owns the largest North American appliance brand family, all operating with shared parts infrastructure while maintaining distinct positioning. <b>JennAir</b> (luxury, 2020 Rise+Nord relaunch), <b>KitchenAid</b> (premium with cooking emphasis), <b>Whirlpool</b> (mainstream premium, this page), <b>Maytag</b> (mass-market heavy-duty positioning), <b>Amana</b> (value-tier), <b>Roper</b> (entry-tier). Wall ovens ship from Whirlpool, JennAir, KitchenAid, Maytag, and Amana; Roper focuses on laundry. For LA service, the shared Whirlpool Corporation parts network means Whirlpool wall oven parts share substantial commonality with comparable Maytag + Amana wall oven parts, bake elements, convection fan motors, many sensor + control platforms interchange at the component level across the mid-tier family. Parts supply runs through Whirlpool's North American distribution which is one of the largest appliance-parts networks in the US." },
  { q: "What's AccuBake and True Convection on a Whirlpool wall oven?", a: "<b>AccuBake</b> is Whirlpool's temperature-management system, sensor-guided temperature control that reduces cavity temperature fluctuation versus thermostat-only control. Practical cooking benefit: more consistent baking, less cold/hot spots across the cavity. Service: AccuBake depends on additional temperature sensors beyond the primary cavity thermostat; sensor drift can cause cycle-temperature issues requiring sensor replacement rather than control board. <b>True Convection</b> is Whirlpool's third-element convection implementation, dedicated heating element around the convection fan (same approach as GE Profile's True European Convection), giving more even heat distribution in multi-rack cooking. True Convection can fail independently of the main bake element, diagnostic verifies which element is the issue." },
  { q: "Whirlpool Smart Wi-Fi integration, what's the service pattern?", a: "Whirlpool Smart (branded as \"Whirlpool App\" or with partnership integrations for Alexa + Google Home) is Whirlpool's Wi-Fi + app platform. Common service scenarios: Wi-Fi connectivity drops after router firmware updates (network-side fix), app pairing lost after appliance firmware updates (re-pair sequence), voice-assistant integration fails (platform-side issue usually resolved by re-authorizing the skill/action). Most Whirlpool Smart issues resolve at firmware + connectivity layer without hardware replacement. Smart-feature-specific hardware is minimal on wall ovens, usually just the Wi-Fi module integrated into the main control board." },
  { q: "What does Whirlpool wall oven repair cost in LA?", a: "Residential diagnostic is $89, waived when you authorize the repair. Whirlpool wall oven service at mass-market pricing: bake element $220-$380; broil element $220-$380; True Convection third-element $260-$440; convection fan motor $280-$480; control board $380-$660; AccuBake secondary sensor $180-$340; primary temperature sensor $180-$320; door hinge $220-$380; door glass $320-$560; thermostat $240-$400; Whirlpool Smart firmware + connectivity reset $180-$320; self-clean door-lock motor $220-$380; self-clean thermal sensor $180-$320; double wall oven per-cavity service $300-$560. Whirlpool Corporation distribution 1-3 days common parts, 3-5 days specialty components, among the strongest parts availability in the US appliance-repair market." },

    {
      q: "Where can I find the official Whirlpool manual or warranty information?",
      a: `For official Whirlpool documentation, warranty registration, and authorized service locator, visit <a href="https://www.whirlpool.com/service-and-support.html" rel="nofollow noopener" target="_blank">Whirlpool service</a>. Our technicians work independently of Whirlpool's factory service network - we're often faster and available same-day in Southern California.`
    },
  ];

const schemaJsons = [
